Q1. What is the main method in Java?
A: It's the entry point of any Java application.
public static void main(String[] args) { }

Q2. What is the file extension of a Java source file?
A: .java (compiled to .class by the compiler)

Q3. What are the main data types in Java?
A: Primitive: int, float, double, char, boolean, byte, short, long
   Non-Primitive: String, Arrays, Objects, etc.

Q4. What is the difference between int and Integer?
A: int is a primitive type; Integer is a wrapper class (object).

Q5. What are the types of operators in Java?
Arithmetic: + - * / %
Relational: == != > < >= <=
Logical: && || !
Assignment: = += -= *=

Q6. What is type casting?
Converting one data type into another:
Implicit (Widening): int to long
Explicit (Narrowing): double to int → int a = (int) 5.67;

Q7. How does the if-else statement work in Java?
A: It evaluates a boolean condition and runs code accordingly.
if (marks >= 50) {
   System.out.println("Pass");
} else {
   System.out.println("Fail");
}

Q8. Can we nest if statements?
A: Yes. if inside another if block is called nested if.

Q9. How do you declare and initialize an array in Java?
int[] nums = new int[5];  // declaration
int[] values = {1, 2, 3}; // initialization

Q10. How do you find the length of an array?
A: array.length

Q11. Are strings mutable in Java?
A: No. Strings are immutable. Any change creates a new string.

Q12. What are some common String methods?
length()
charAt(index)
substring(start, end)
equals(), equalsIgnoreCase()
contains(), indexOf()
toLowerCase(), toUpperCase()

Q13. How do you take user input in Java?
Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
int a = sc.nextInt();
String s = sc.nextLine();

Q14. When do you use switch over if-else?
Use switch when you have multiple constant values to check against a variable.

Q15. Write a simple switch example.
switch (day) {
  case 1: System.out.println("Mon"); break;
  case 2: System.out.println("Tue"); break;
  default: System.out.println("Other day");
}

Q16. What is the difference between == and .equals() for Strings?
== checks memory reference (address)
.equals() checks actual content/value

Q17. What happens if you divide by zero in Java?
For integers → ArithmeticException
For doubles → Infinity